    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Elian: Other Views</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Hazel Kahan letter on Apr 26 article holds Elian Gonzalez is entitled to confidentiality about his psychological condition</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What a Smile Hides: Unknown Effects of Cuban Boy's Ordeal'' (news article, April 26): Does there not come a point in this whole sorry business when Elian Gonzalez is entitled to confidentiality about his psychological condition?</p>
        <p>When will the legions of psychiatric experts, whether or not they have had personal contact with the boy, begin holding their tongues and maintaining appropriate silence according to the established canons of their profession?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What a Smile Hides: Unknown Effects of Cuban Boy's Ordeal'' (news article, April 26): Does there not come a point in this whole sorry business when Elian Gonzalez is entitled to confidentiality about his psychological condition?</p>
        <p>When will the legions of psychiatric experts, whether or not they have had personal contact with the boy, begin holding their tongues and maintaining appropriate silence according to the established canons of their profession?</p>
        <p>An air of impropriety surrounds the analyses of Elian's relationships with his parents and the long-term ramifications caused by his devastating experiences. As voracious onlookers, we are continuing the public media humiliation to which his Miami relatives have exposed him all these months.</p>
        <p>AZEL  KAHAN  Mattituck, N.Y., April 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
